Education provider AdvTech has acquired a 51% stake in distance learning institution, the University of Africa (UoA) for an undisclosed amount.The UoA is headquartered in Zambia and offers qualifications to students from across the continent in Commerce, Teacher Education, Engineering &amp; Bio Science, and Law &amp; Humanities.This acquisition is the first since the International Finance Corporation invested in AdvTech in 2016 to support its expansion strategy, and is AdvTech s first tertiary partnership outside of South Africa.The UoA was founded in 2006 and now has over 2000 students and offers 22 Bachelors, eight Masters and a Doctoral degree.The addition of UoA will swell AdvTech s tertiary division to ten brands across 26 sites in sub-Saharan Africa. These include the Vega School of Brand Leadership, Rosebank College, Varsity College, The Design School of Southern Africa and Oxbridge Academy, a long-distance education institution, which it acquired last year.Peter Kriel, General Manager of The Independent Institute of Education (The IIE), which is responsible for ensuring academic excellence at AdvTech s tertiary brands, has been appointed tothe UoA Council. The IIE will help benchmark the UoA s degree and diploma programmes against international best practice. It will also advise on future appointments of qualified and experienced lecturers and academics, develop work-focused curricula created in conjunction with industry experts, and assist with teaching and delivery methods that are constantly innovated in line with global advancements.